@@eThe Eastern Desert -- Trade Syndic Briefing@@N

The eastern desert is distant from Kiess, separated by the full
length of Roc Road and Midgaard's eastern reach. But the @@yTrade
Syndics@@N study it with professional fascination, because the desert
demonstrates what happens when @@ylogistics authority@@N becomes the
only authority -- and then fails.

The @@yKeepers of Measure@@N governed by calibration: road stones set
to star angles, cistern basins graded by seasonal drift, caravan
levies assessed in @@Wwater rights@@N rather than coin. Every Syndic
apprentice reads the Keeper case studies. Their @@yTwelve Obelisk
Lines@@N were instruments, not monuments -- shadow-cast systems that
encoded direction, time, water volume, and legal status in a single
glyph. The Syndics call this @@Wfunctional inscription@@N, and our own
convoy compacts borrow the principle: a document should @@ywork@@N, not
merely record.

The @@rcharter road system@@N is the part that speaks loudest to Kiess.
Charter stones bore distance, toll rates, and witness seals. Convoy
formation rules and ration stamps kept fragile water supplies in
balance. This is infrastructure we recognize -- it is what our
convoy marshals do along Roc Road, adapted for sand instead of
forest.

Then the @@dIseth Reach@@N dried. The river that fed every cistern and
justified every charter simply ceased. Water courts became war
tribunals. The @@rCharter Wars@@N erupted as armed factions enforced
legal claims at spearpoint. Reavers who outlasted their employers
became the desert's modern predators -- and they retained the
@@yprocedural habits@@N of the system that created them: seizure
inventories, stamped claim-slates, ritualized inspections.

This is the lesson @@dWall Command@@N posts on every gatehouse board:
@@rwhen route maintenance fails, the route does not simply close.@@N
It becomes contested ground where every faction claims the old
authority's tools without its obligations. The charter rods become
extortion instruments. The ration stamps become currency of
coercion.

The @@yPrism archive@@N holds a Syndic commentary that every new trade
clerk must read: @@d"The Keepers measured correctly and governed
wisely. The desert still consumed them, because measurement
without maintenance is a sealed warrant against the future."@@N

Kiess does not trade directly in the eastern desert. But every
Syndic who negotiates a convoy compact knows: the difference
between a living road and a dead one is not law. It is whether
anyone still repairs the stones.
